segments.text: The Doctor of Veterinarian Medicine degree was first granted at Texas A&M in 1920.
Yeah.
But the school didn't grant a master's degree in Veterinarian Medicine or a doctor, well the doctor's degree was first issued in 1955.
I was wondering why did it take so long?
Well because
The enrollment was relatively small, and we didn't have research individuals.
Most of them had a degree in veterinary medicine, but did not have any advanced degrees in research, like master's and PhD.
that had to come gradually as more of the staff had an opportunity to get, in other words, lots of them would have to take courses and take them four, five, six years to get a master's degree.
So it took quite a while to build up a backlog of individuals that were research-minded.
To be a good research man, you've got to be research minded.
And originally, we were trying to turn out clinicians.
Right.
And research was something else.
Now it wasn't until after the war that they really started putting pressure on.
Who's they?
Who's they?
The college authorities, the university authorities.
Okay.
on departments to get advanced degrees and do research.
Up to that time, A&M was not a great research institution.
And then, in other words, it was sometime between, or it was right after the Second World War, as a matter of fact, that the emphasis of the School of Veterinarian Medicine changed.
one from, and correct me if I'm wrong, a training ground for clinicians to a much more specialized and a much more research-oriented school?
Yes.
I'd say that's right.
And do you think that the specialization has had an impact on the quality of education?
That's hard to evaluate, for me to evaluate.
Now, a man that's doing research, I'll say this, he likes in his classes, he'll always be drumming his students on what
he has discovered in research or what research he's doing and he's going to put a lot of emphasis on his research.
Whereas the men who were teaching as more or less clinicians put it more on the practical side.
So I think you can go as far as training.
If you're going to train veterinarians to be veterinarians, you can go overboard
on research.
You'd much rather have them good surgeons or good internal medicine or something of that nature rather than full of a bunch of research statistics.
There's after all, there's just so much time.
Right, absolutely.
You're either going to turn out a good clinician or a good research man.
And when does the student make up his mind if he wants to be a clinician or if he wants to go on for an advanced degree?
It has to be after he graduates.
After he gets his doctorate in medicine.
That's right.
OK. You know, as you well know, in the last half century, there's been a trend in most fields, especially in medicine, it seems to me,
a trend from training general practitioners to specialists.
We can even see this in the field of history.
American historians to people who are studying just recent American history, or people who are just studying economic American history, or something like that.
Much more specialization.
Is that the same tendency in veterinarian medicine?
Seems to be, yes.
In other words, as you get these staff members who are PhDs, now bear in mind, that's a research.
They're going to want to teach that one specialty.
That's the thing they know the best, and that's what they should be teaching.
So, yes, there's quite a difference there.
Are there any other reasons besides these advanced degree people?
Are there any other reasons, do you think, for more specialization?
Well, it's just personal preference.
Just like one man going to small animals and one man going to large animals, it's just what you'd like to do.
No, if you want to be a research man, you can't be a practitioner, because you'd starve to death.
Somebody has to foot the bill for research.
In most cases, it's the government.
Let's talk about your duties from the Second World War to the present.
You were the head of
Veterinarian Hygiene, and then you were Assistant Dean in Curricular Affairs.
We talked about Veterinarian Hygiene.
Can you tell us about the Assistant Dean in Curricular Affairs?
What did you do there?
What were your functions and duties?
I served just as a dean.
The Dean Boughton had a stroke and was incapacitated.
So I was acting dean.
Hiring and firing and- Everything, yeah.
Salaries and- The whole works.
All administrative.
How'd you like that?
Not too much.
Why not?
It's pretty draggy.
You get into administration, a lot of paperwork, and here there's always somebody coming up with some fool questionnaire that they want you to fill out.
You're up in cloud nine half the time.
So, I enjoyed it all right, but there's lots of pressures there that are not too enjoyable.
Yeah, you're always having to do things that you'd rather not do.
because they have to be done.
For example?
Well, there's always all kinds of meetings to go to all over the country, one kind or another.
All these associations of universities and all that, and that gets pretty tiresome.
and it takes up a lot of time that you'd rather be doing something else with.
And while you had this position, did you have any classroom responsibilities?
Yeah, I went on with, sure.
So this is sort of an extra burden.
That's right.
That's what it amounted to.
Somebody had to do it and they asked me to do it.
So I did it.
Why do you think they asked you?
I don't know.
Because they liked me.
I don't know.
At least the ones that were in there at the time.
But I don't know why they asked me.
Now, after that position, you were head of the Department of Public Health.
In what way was that different than being head of the Department of Veterinary and Hygiene?
Same thing.
Just a different name?
Just a different name.
I told you in the beginning that veterinary hygiene was a poor choice of terms.
But they couldn't come up with a better one.
During 30 years, you must have been on some important committees.
Would you like to talk about that?
Golly, I can't remember the committees I was on.
I was on the athletic council one time, and I was on other committees, but I can't remember what they were now.
They'd function for a while, they'd do what they had to do and be disbanded.
That was kind of a constant thing going on all the time.
You'd be appointed to a committee or else you'd be asked or told to do certain things and I can't remember all those.
Then let's go back to what we were just talking about and that is research.
I have a couple of quick questions on research.
It appears that research in
American Veterinarian Medicine has made some great strides in the last 30 years or so.
What is the School of Veterinary, what fields of research are we strong in at the School of Veterinarian Medicine here?
I can't answer that.
I don't know.
Well I can't, I know
when I was out there, I guess, poultry diseases.
They were strong on poultry diseases.
That's about the only thing we were strong on as far as research is concerned that I can think of at that time.
Not with cattle research?
You know, it just seems to me, Texas, cattle,
Texas A&M School of Veterinary Medicine probably would be pretty strong in cattle.
Well, yes, but your teaching staff didn't have much time for research.
Now, Dr. Schmidt, principally that was his job.
He was always doing research or troubleshooting.
He did a lot of research on pyroplasmosis, pyroplasmosis.
Then they did some on anaplasmosis.
They did quite a bit on anaplasmosis.
They did have, they did some work on, they had a black-legged
research project and an anthrax research project.
And, but I don't, I came, I wasn't too familiar with the prize.
See, that was separate.
Right.
I understand that.
I was just, I just wanted your ideas on this.
During your last few years here, here, we, the nation seemed, and I've talked to people up at Purdue about this, the nation and
seemed to go through a green revolution they called it, the green revolution in the 1960s and the increase in production and new strains of wheat and all, things like that.
Do you remember if that was a topic of conversation here in your last four or five years or did it have any impact at all?
No, not on me.
Okay, fine, fine.
And that brings me, speaking on a more international scene, that brings me to another question.
That is international studies.
Did you have any role whatsoever in international studies in the School of Veterinary Medicine?
Not in the School of Veterinary Medicine.
Now I did attend some conferences that had to do with international veterinary problems, but I don't think it affected us there in the veterinary college.

It was just a question of listening to these people from various countries talk about their problems, and usually it was the government men that, that is the American government men, veterinarians and whatnot, that more or less
call the shots because they were putting up all the money.
Sure, sure.
In other words, you didn't spend any time overseas.
No.
For example, Dr. Turk spent some time in South America.
Oh, he went to Peru once.
No.
Now Ted Franklin spent more time out of the country, I guess, than anybody else.
He was in the Dominican Republic for a while.
And where else did he go?
I think he went to Africa for a while.
And well, there's a man in parasitology that was in Africa for a year.
When did we start having these more international contacts?
After World War I, II.
After World War II?
In the late 1940s and then the 50s?
Yeah.
Mostly in the 50s, I'd say.
Oh lots of, some of these South American countries would want to set up a veterinary school or start a veterinary school.
They'd ask someone to come down and help them.
Sure, right.
They'd say they wanted to ask me to go to Venezuela one time, but I wasn't interested.
That was after I retired.
I think it was Venezuela, somewhere down there.
And I've forgotten what they called those programs.
Anyway, they had a,

government was also sponsoring another program that had to do with the retired people, not necessarily in veterinary medicine, but businessmen, creamery operators, owners of, and who had retired, had to go to Thailand or somewhere and set up, help them set up a creamery over there.
But no, it didn't affect us too much.
Now could we turn back to your service, your personal service over almost 30 years in the vet school.
In every man's career, really there are high points and low points you might say.
Could you reflect on what you feel
were perhaps your shortcomings or things that you thought you wanted to complete, but you just for some reason didn't, and then on what you feel are your achievements, things that you did achieve.
No, I don't think I have anything that I
that strikes me as being a high point or a low point in my career is more or less doing things that needed to be done.
I can't think of it as being a high point or a low point.
It was more or less of a plateau all the way through for me.
How about strengths?
strengths or weaknesses.
What fields did you feel that you made a strong contribution teaching?
Well, I guess it was in developing that veterinary public health program because there was nothing there when I went there.
And I had to start from scratch and develop it.
And well, I'm still developing it.
When I left there, Dr. Russell had come there with me.
I think that was in about 1957, 58.
he had a master's public health that he'd gotten at Tulane and then we developed some of course an epidemiology that veterinary, well public health and this epidemiology of course is
how different diseases are transmitted.
In other words, the history of the outbreak, that sort of thing, and how it behaves.
And then while he was there, he got his PhD there at A&M, and he's still out there.
I think he teaches mostly epidemiology now.
So I don't know that there's any, that I have any high points.
What about your students in veterinary or in public health?
Where were most of those people placed and what are they doing?
Well, a lot of them, after they graduated of course,
They don't come to any, they don't take veterinary medicine to become veterinary hygienists or anything of that nature.
They come there to become practitioners.
Now a lot of them, after they graduated, they went to the service and a lot of them are in public health work.
I see.
As a result of that, and
I hope that what we gave them in veterinary hygiene and veterinary public health was a stepping stone to help them while they were in the service.
Now most of them that didn't go to the service don't go into public health.
For some reason or other they become, while they're in the service, since they're
principal job is public health.
I think a lot of them go into public health work when they get out of the service.
Rather than go into, well they've been out of contact with practice, with the practice of veterinary medicine, and they prefer to go into public health work.
rather than try to catch up on what's happened in the clinical subjects and go into practice.
Now that's a feeling I have.
OK.
I have a final question.
We've talked about a number of changes in the School of Vet and Medicine since the 1920s to your retirement in 1965.
along with your thoughts on a lot of these changes.
What have I missed?
Is there anything that I haven't talked about or asked that you'd like to discuss?
No, I think you've about cleaned me out.
I can't say that I can think of anything more that I can throw in there.
Anything with your career would
that you'd like to talk about.
I'm sure there's probably something in there that I've missed about your personal career that you might.
Oh, my personal career I guess has been pretty uninteresting.
Uninteresting to anybody else but me.
I had lots of good experiences.
I appreciate all of them.
All of them taught me something when I was in practice and then working for the city in Beaumont and coming to A&M and trying to develop a course or courses in, well, veterinary hygiene at that time.
later became Veterinary Public Health.
But as far as really exciting points, I have none that I can think of.
Okay, and you don't think that there's any other topics that we should discuss that I might have missed?
I can't think of anything right now.
As I tell most people, I'll think about it about midnight and I'll call you.
But no, I can't think of anything else right now.
Okay, then this ends our interview with Dr. Fred Jaggi.
Thank you very much.
Been a pleasure.
